# AI Pairing Context: distributed-lottery-analyzer

## Project Overview
A highly parallelized, distributed application designed to run on top of the custom `distributed-compute-operator` which has already been created at https://github.com/Rosalita/distributed-compute-operator

This project has one main goal using the complete historical datasets (including prize breakdowns) for major UK National Lottery games (Lotto, Euromillions, Thunderball, and Set For Life):
1. **Most Profitable Line Finder:** Distribute the total possible combination space across worker pods to brute-force evaluate every single possible ticket against all historical draws, finding the specific line for each game that would have paid out the most total money over all time.


## Architecture (Tightly-Coupled Distributed Workload)
This application is packaged as a single Docker container but uses its networking hostname to determine its role at runtime.

### The Leader Pod (`<job-name>-leader`)
- **Data Manager:** Loads the historical datasets (winning numbers and prize values per tier) for all lottery games into memory on startup.
- **Global Observer & Dispatcher:** Assigns chunks of the total combination space (e.g., lines starting with 1, lines starting with 2) to connecting workers. Runs a gRPC/TCP server to receive and aggregate the highest-earning lines found by the workers.

### The Worker Pods (`<job-name>-worker-X`)
- **Combination Chunk Processing:** Each worker pod receives a specific subset of the millions of possible ticket combinations from the leader.
- **Historical Evaluation:** Workers rapidly simulate playing their assigned combinations across every historical draw, calculating the total monetary payout for each line based on historical prize tiers.
- **Result Reporting:** Once a worker finishes evaluating its chunk, it sends the top-earning lines and their total historical profit back to the leader over predictable Headless Service DNS.

## Progress So Far
- Project conceptualized.
- Infrastructure (Custom Kubernetes Operator) is complete and tested in the `distributed-compute-operator` repository.
- Go module initialized (`github.com/Rosalita/distributed-lottery-analyzer`).
- Basic project structure established (`cmd/analyser`, `internal/data`, `cmd/getdrawhistory`).
- Built a standalone data-gathering script (`cmd/getdrawhistory`) that:
  - Fetches the latest 180-day summary CSVs for all 4 games and merges them into a deduplicated, sorted main CSV.
  - Extracts draw numbers and dynamically downloads the detailed prize breakdown JSON files for every historical draw.
  - Implements smart caching to skip previously downloaded files and respect API rate limits.
- Generic JSON data models (`DrawDetailsResponse`, etc.) defined to map the National Lottery API responses.
- **Data Loading Phase Complete:** Created the `cmd/analyser/internal/data` package. The Leader pod successfully loads all JSON files into memory at startup as a fast-lookup map (`map[string]map[int]DrawDetails`).
- Added `CalculateMatches` and `GetPrize` helper methods to the data models to prepare for rapid brute-force evaluation.

## Next Steps for Development
### 1. Core Logic Implementation (Evaluator)
- Build the brute-force evaluation engine to calculate total historical profit for a given line.
- Create a combination generator to split the millions of possible tickets into predictable chunks.

### 2. Distributed Networking
- Build the Dispatcher logic on the Leader to hand out chunks of combinations.
- Build the TCP/gRPC communication for workers to fetch chunks and report results.

### 3. Containerization & Deployment
- Write the `Dockerfile`.
- Create the `DistributedJob` custom resource YAML to deploy the solver to the Kubernetes cluster.